---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
import { defaultLang } from '../i18n/translations';

const lang = defaultLang;
---

<Layout title="What the pilot taught us | POLICE-COM" lang={lang}>
  <section class="page-hero">
    <div class="container">
      <span class="section-label">Pilot &amp; best practice</span>
      <h1 class="section-title animate-in">What the pilot taught us</h1>
      <p class="section-subtitle animate-in delay-1">
        Honest findings from piloting POL-COM with police trainers, probation officers and
        security professionals — and what we changed in response.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="container narrow">
      <p class="lead">
        POL-COM was piloted in Czechia, Lithuania and Romania with police cadets, trainers and
        security professionals. We asked participants to be critical rather than polite.
        Average satisfaction with the pilot training was 4.0 out of 5 and platform usability
        4.2 out of 5 — but the criticism was the useful part. This page summarises what we
        heard, what we changed, what we did not manage to fix, and what we would advise anyone
        building similar training.
      </p>

      <h2 class="block-title">What we heard</h2>
      <div class="finding">
        <h3>“Too much text.”</h3>
        <p>Participants found the courses information-dense and said today's learners expect
        video and interactive formats rather than long reading materials.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="finding">
        <h3>“Every module looked different.”</h3>
        <p>Materials were presented in a different style in each module, so learners had to
        reorient themselves each time.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="finding">
        <h3>“Everything had to be downloaded.”</h3>
        <p>Materials were offered as downloads rather than readable directly in the platform,
        which made the environment feel heavier than necessary.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="finding">
        <h3>“Where are the usage rights?”</h3>
        <p>Trainers were told the videos could be reused elsewhere, but could not find any
        licensing information saying so.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="finding">
        <h3>“Activities repeated themselves.”</h3>
        <p>Some exercises felt too simple for adult professionals and cycled through similar
        patterns; a few definitions were imprecise.</p>
      </div>

      <h2 class="block-title">What we changed</h2>
      <ul class="did-list">
        <li><strong>Licensing is now explicit.</strong> Every training material carries a
        CC BY 4.0 notice and EU funding attribution, so trainers know exactly what they may
        reuse and how to credit it.</li>
        <li><strong>Knowledge checks in the modules.</strong> Interactive exercises and
        quizzes let learners test what they retained, as requested during the pilot.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2 class="block-title">What we only partly solved</h2>
      <p>Two findings deserve an honest answer rather than a claim of success.</p>
      <ul class="did-list">
        <li><strong>Consistency across modules.</strong> The methodology itself was designed
        as one shared framework — including the five study phases every module follows — from
        the very beginning. In practice each partner implemented that framework somewhat
        differently on the learning platform, and harmonising all six modules retrospectively
        would have meant rebuilding them. On this website we took a different route: materials
        can be browsed and downloaded selectively, so trainers assemble the sequence they
        need. That addresses part of the problem, not all of it.</li>
        <li><strong>Less text, more audiovisual content.</strong> This is a real limitation of
        the current version. The materials remain more text-heavy than participants would
        like, and it is the clearest direction for any future iteration of the programme.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2 class="block-title">What we would tell others</h2>
      <ol class="advice-list">
        <li><strong>Ask for criticism explicitly.</strong> Politeness produces useless
        feedback. Our most valuable input came from participants who were told that pointing
        out weaknesses was the point of the exercise.</li>
        <li><strong>Decide the licence before you produce, not after.</strong> Retro-fitting
        attribution to hundreds of files is expensive; one decision at the start prevents it.</li>
        <li><strong>Agree the implementation, not only the methodology.</strong> A shared
        framework on paper still leaves room for six different interpretations in practice.
        Agree early how the framework will look in the platform, not just what it contains.</li>
        <li><strong>Pilot with the real audience, not with colleagues.</strong> Practitioners
        spotted issues — pace, realism, repetition — that internal review had passed over.</li>
        <li><strong>Budget for revision, not just production.</strong> A pilot is only useful
        if time and money remain to act on what it finds.</li>
      </ol>

      <div class="cta-row">
        <a href="https://polcom-training.eu/" class="btn btn-primary" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Explore the training platform</a>
        <a href="/materials/" class="btn btn-secondary">Browse the materials</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>

<style>
  .page-hero {
    padding: calc(72px + 4rem) 0 3.5rem;
    background: var(--color-bg-elevated);
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--color-border);
  }

  .btn {
    display: inline-flex;
    align-items: center;
    gap: 0.5rem;
    padding: 0.75rem 1.5rem;
    font-family: var(--font-body);
    font-size: 0.9rem;
    font-weight: 600;
    border-radius: var(--radius-sm);
    transition: all 0.25s;
    text-decoration: none;
  }

  .btn-primary {
    background: var(--color-accent);
    color: #fff;
  }

  .btn-primary:hover { background: var(--color-accent-light); }

  .btn-secondary {
    background: transparent;
    color: var(--color-accent);
    border: 1px solid var(--color-border);
  }

  .btn-secondary:hover { border-color: var(--color-accent); }

  .narrow { max-width: 780px; }

  .lead {
    font-size: 1.0625rem;
    line-height: 1.75;
    color: var(--color-text-muted);
    margin-bottom: 2.5rem;
  }

  .block-title {
    font-family: var(--font-body);
    font-size: 1.125rem;
    font-weight: 700;
    color: var(--color-text);
    margin: 2.5rem 0 1rem;
    padding-bottom: 0.5rem;
    border-bottom: 2px solid var(--color-accent);
  }

  .finding {
    background: var(--color-bg-card);
    border: 1px solid var(--color-border);
    border-left: 3px solid var(--color-accent);
    border-radius: var(--radius);
    padding: 1rem 1.25rem;
    margin-bottom: 0.875rem;
  }

  .finding h3 {
    font-family: var(--font-body);
    font-size: 0.9375rem;
    font-weight: 600;
    color: var(--color-text);
    margin-bottom: 0.375rem;
  }

  .finding p {
    font-size: 0.875rem;
    color: var(--color-text-muted);
    margin: 0;
  }

  .did-list, .advice-list {
    padding-left: 1.25rem;
    margin-bottom: 1rem;
  }

  .did-list li, .advice-list li {
    font-size: 0.9375rem;
    line-height: 1.7;
    color: var(--color-text-muted);
    margin-bottom: 0.75rem;
  }

  .did-list strong, .advice-list strong { color: var(--color-text); }

  .cta-row {
    display: flex;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
    gap: 0.75rem;
    margin-top: 2.5rem;
  }
</style>
